<subSubSection box="[151,964,1465,1492]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,964,1465,1492]" box="[151,964,1465,1492]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,964,1465,1492]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,964,1465,1492]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
Keys for the separation of the subspecies of 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[698,964,1465,1492]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Herbst" baseAuthorityYear="1784" box="[698,959,1465,1492]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ungaricus">Ropalopus ungaricus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="570" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1538,1816]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
The complex 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Herbst" baseAuthorityYear="1784" box="[304,542,1538,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ungaricus">
<emphasis box="[304,542,1538,1564]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">Ropalopus ungaricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be divided into two group characterized by the punctures of pronotum. The first group integrated by the subspecies 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Herbst" baseAuthorityYear="1784" box="[591,782,1574,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ungaricus" subGenus="Ropalopus">
<emphasis box="[591,615,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[630,655,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[670,782,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">ungaricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Germar" baseAuthorityYear="1824" box="[795,990,1574,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insubricus" subGenus="Ropalopus">
<emphasis box="[795,819,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[834,858,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[873,990,1574,1600]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">insubricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1042,1210,1574,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gallicus" subGenus="Ropalopus">
<emphasis box="[1042,1067,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1082,1106,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1121,1210,1574,1600]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">gallicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is defined by a pronotum with a discal area smooth in the males and almost smooth in his whole surface in the females. In the second group formed by the subspecies 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rapuzzi" authorityYear="2017" box="[518,670,1646,1672]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boreki" subGenus="Ropalopus">
<emphasis box="[518,542,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[559,583,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[600,670,1646,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">boreki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[686,830,1646,1672]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ossae" subGenus="Ropalopus">
<emphasis box="[686,710,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[727,751,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[768,830,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">ossae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stierlin" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[845,1005,1646,1672]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siculus" subGenus="Ropalopus">
<emphasis box="[845,869,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[886,910,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[927,1005,1646,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">siculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="López &amp; Baena, 2022" authorityName="López &amp; Baena" authorityYear="2022" box="[1061,1278,1646,1672]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occidentalis" status="ssp. nov." subGenus="Ropalopus">
<emphasis box="[1061,1085,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1102,1126,1647,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1143,1278,1646,1672]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">occidentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1286,1387,1646,1672]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1286,1387,1646,1672]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" rank="subSpecies">ssp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the pronotum in both sexes is densely punctate or rugose, often with small median unpunctured and lustrous area near base. 
<bibRefCitation author="Karpinski, L. &amp; Szczepanski, W. T. &amp; Kruszelnicki, L." box="[216,473,1718,1744]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" pagination="1176 - 1216" refId="ref7070" refString="Karpinski, L., Szczepanski, W. T. &amp; Kruszelnicki, L. (2020) Revision of the Ropalopus ungaricus / insubricus group (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae: Callidiini) from the western Palaearctic region. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 189, 1176 - 1216. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / zoolinnean / zlz 154" type="journal article" year="2020">
Karpiński 
<emphasis box="[334,384,1718,1744]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">et al</emphasis>
. (2020)
</bibRefCitation>
have used these features in his key for the separation of the subspecies of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Herbst" baseAuthorityYear="1784" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ungaricus">Ropalopus ungaricus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The followings artificial keys modify the published by 
<bibRefCitation author="Karpinski, L. &amp; Szczepanski, W. T. &amp; Kruszelnicki, L." box="[884,1136,1754,1780]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" pagination="1176 - 1216" refId="ref7070" refString="Karpinski, L., Szczepanski, W. T. &amp; Kruszelnicki, L. (2020) Revision of the Ropalopus ungaricus / insubricus group (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae: Callidiini) from the western Palaearctic region. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 189, 1176 - 1216. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / zoolinnean / zlz 154" type="journal article" year="2020">
Karpiński 
<emphasis box="[1001,1049,1754,1780]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">et al</emphasis>
. (2020)
</bibRefCitation>
to include the new subspecies and allow an easy separation of all known subspecies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="571" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" type="key">
<key lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="571" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<keyStep pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1859,2027]" box="[151,1436,1859,1881]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1859,1881]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">1. Ventral surface covered with a dense and yellowish pubescence................................................. 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1859,2027]" box="[151,1436,1888,1910]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1888,1910]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">-. Ventral surface covered with sparse black hairs.............................................................. 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1859,2027]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<keyLead pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
2. Pronotum with a smooth discal rhomboid area in the males and almost smooth in his whole surface in the females. Located in southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[352,420,1947,1968]" name="France" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">France</collectingCountry>
...................................................................... 
<emphasis box="[1267,1288,1947,1968]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1302,1323,1947,1968]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1336,1436,1947,1968]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
u. 
<taxonomicName box="[1360,1436,1947,1968]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gallicus">gallicus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1859,2027]" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
<keyLead pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
-. Pronotum in both sexes densely punctate or rugose, often with small median unpunctured area near base. Endemic to 
<collectingRegion box="[1355,1412,1976,1998]" country="Italy" name="Sicilia" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">Sicily</collectingRegion>
......................................................................................... 
<emphasis box="[1276,1298,2006,2027]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1311,1332,2006,2027]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1346,1437,2005,2027]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="570">
u. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stierlin" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[1370,1437,2005,2026]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siculus">siculus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
3. Elytral shiny and sculpture clearly of 
<specimenCount box="[589,685,152,173]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
. In the metallic basal half part there are deeper and larger isolated points (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1854,1878]" captionTargetBox="[426,1161,1202,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-1152@14.[426,1161,1202,1831]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 23. Elytral sculpture on basal half of R. (R.) ungaricus boreki (Photo: Karpiński et al. 2020)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655524" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655524/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) while in the matt distal half the points are much smaller and denser; pronotum unevenly tapered towards anterior and posterior margins, wide and raised at base then cordate; antennae in males as long as elytra; lateral lobes of tegmen long and slender, parallel sided with external margin concave and relatively long hairs on top. Restricted to Southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1267,1335,240,261]" name="Greece" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Greece</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion country="Greece" name="Peloponnisos" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Peloponnese</collectingRegion>
Peninsula)........................................................................... 
<emphasis box="[1282,1304,269,290]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1317,1339,269,290]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1352,1436,269,290]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
u. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rapuzzi" authorityYear="2017" box="[1376,1436,269,290]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boreki">boreki</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
-. Elytra with similar shiny in the basal and distal parts. Elytral sculpture more uniform on whole surface, changing gradually in depth and density of points towards end, the sculpture is mainly made by indistinct points with creased and convex surface between them (
<figureCitation box="[373,441,357,379]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="5.[151,250,964,988]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[482,1105,181,940]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 6. Elytral sculpture of the basal half of the elytra of the holotypus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6672424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6672424/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[451,465,357,378]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1868,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-37@5.[570,1016,1013,1845]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 7. Elytral sculpture fom medium to apex of holotypus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6672426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6672426/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">7</figureCitation>
), greenish brown; pronotum evenly tapered towards anterior and posterior margin.............. 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
4. Pronotum with a smooth discal rhomboid area in the males and almost smooth in his whole surface in the females (
<figureCitation box="[1317,1432,386,408]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–25" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1279,1303]" captionTargetBox="[414,1174,181,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-19@15.[414,1174,181,1255]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 24–25. Male pronotum of R. (R.) ungaricus ungaricus and R. (R.) ungaricus insubricus (Photo: Karpiński et al. 2020)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655526" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655526/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Figs. 24, 25</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[226,253,415,437]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[371,1217,1363,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-48@15.[371,1217,1363,1924]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 26. Female pronotum of R. (R.) ungaricus ungaricus (Photo: Karpiński et al. 2020)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655530/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">26</figureCitation>
)................................................................................................. 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
-. Pronotum in both sexes densely punctate or rugose, often with small median unpunctured area near base (
<figureCitation box="[1243,1324,445,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1910,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-50@8.[415,1173,1262,1887]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 13. Pronotum of the allotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6672436" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6672436/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Figs. 13</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1334,1432,445,467]" captionStart="FIGURES 14-16" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1247,1271]" captionTargetBox="[268,1320,181,1222]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[268,1320,181,1223]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 14-16. Variability on sides and lustrous area of pronotum in males." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655508/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">14, 15, 16</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[226,252,474,495]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="9.[151,250,2012,2036]" captionTargetId="figure-35@9.[335,1252,1295,1988]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 17. Variability on punctuation of pronotum in females." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6672442" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6672442/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">17</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[262,325,474,496]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–28" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1382,1406]" captionTargetBox="[380,1206,193,1318]" captionTargetId="figure-28@16.[380,1207,181,1361]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 27–28. Male and female pronotum of R. (R.) ungaricus ossae (Photo: Lech Karpiński)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655534/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">27, 28</figureCitation>
)........................................................................................... 6
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
5. Pronotum clearly tapered towards the margins (
<figureCitation box="[679,750,503,526]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–25" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1279,1303]" captionTargetBox="[414,1174,181,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-19@15.[414,1174,181,1255]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 24–25. Male pronotum of R. (R.) ungaricus ungaricus and R. (R.) ungaricus insubricus (Photo: Karpiński et al. 2020)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655526" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655526/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
); in males the lateral areas densely punctuated and almost merged at the anterior and posterior margins, the central part is occupied by a smooth area without punctuation or at most a barely perceptible; basal half of the elytra slightly and irregularly wrinkled; antennae in males relatively shorter, as long as or at most slightly longer than elytra. Populations living in montane and submontane regions not lower than 
<quantity box="[1108,1171,591,613]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="571" unit="m" value="600.0">600 m</quantity>
a.s.l. Widely distributed in central Europe from eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[495,560,621,642]" name="France" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">France</collectingCountry>
(except south-eastern), central 
<collectingCountry box="[859,904,621,643]" name="Italy" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Italy</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[912,1029,621,642]" name="Serbia" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Montenegro</collectingCountry>
to eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1131,1218,621,643]" name="Romania" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Romania</collectingCountry>
and to the north southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[306,376,650,672]" name="Poland" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Poland</collectingCountry>
........................................................................ 
<emphasis box="[1247,1268,651,672]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1282,1303,651,672]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1316,1436,651,672]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
u. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Herbst" baseAuthorityYear="1784" box="[1340,1436,651,672]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ungaricus">ungaricus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
-. Pronotum irregularly tapered towards margins (
<figureCitation box="[692,766,679,701]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–25" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1279,1303]" captionTargetBox="[414,1174,181,1253]" captionTargetId="figure-19@15.[414,1174,181,1255]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 24–25. Male pronotum of R. (R.) ungaricus ungaricus and R. (R.) ungaricus insubricus (Photo: Karpiński et al. 2020)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655526" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655526/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
); in males the lateral punctuate areas with deeper and narrow punctuation, never merged at the anterior and posterior margins; basal half of elytra without wrinkles and regularly punctured; antennae in males clearly longer than elytra. Populations living at low altitudes, not higher than 
<quantity box="[1164,1226,738,760]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="571" unit="m" value="600.0">600 m</quantity>
a.s.l. This subspecies occurring in Europe from 
<collectingCountry box="[484,528,767,789]" name="Italy" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Italy</collectingCountry>
(northern part) to westernmost 
<collectingCountry box="[843,911,767,789]" name="Turkey" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Turkey</collectingCountry>
and towards the east reaches southern part European 
<collectingCountry box="[226,289,797,819]" name="Russia" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Russia</collectingCountry>
............................................................................................. 
<emphasis box="[1243,1264,797,818]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1278,1299,797,818]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1312,1436,797,818]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
u. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Germar" baseAuthorityYear="1824" box="[1336,1436,797,818]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insubricus">insubricus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
6. Pronotum usually completely, uniformly and densely punctuated, sometimes with a smooth glabrous area near the base in both sexes (
<figureCitation box="[291,399,855,878]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–28" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1382,1406]" captionTargetBox="[380,1206,193,1318]" captionTargetId="figure-28@16.[380,1207,181,1361]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 27–28. Male and female pronotum of R. (R.) ungaricus ossae (Photo: Lech Karpiński)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655534/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Fig. 27, 28</figureCitation>
); antennae in males clearly longer than elytra by almost two last joints; prosternal process relatively narrow and rounded at the apex (
<figureCitation box="[475,549,885,907]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="17.[151,250,893,917]" captionTargetBox="[222,1366,181,869]" captionTargetId="figure-19@17.[222,1366,181,869]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 29. Prosternal process of R. (R.) ungaricus ossae (Photo: Karpiński et al. 2020)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655536/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
); lateral lobes of tegmen short and robust, adjoining at ends, with external margin convex; margin of phallobase roof clearly concave at middle, and relatively short hairs on apex (
<figureCitation box="[1092,1166,914,936]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1986,2010]" captionTargetBox="[550,1038,942,1963]" captionTargetId="figure-40@17.[550,1038,942,1963]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 30. Lateral lobes of R. (R.) ungaricus ossae (Photo: Karpiński et al. 2020)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655538" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655538/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). Located in 
<collectingRegion box="[1295,1436,914,936]" country="Greece" name="Sterea Ellada" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">central Greece</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingRegion box="[232,396,943,965]" country="Greece" name="Thessalia" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Thessaly Region</collectingRegion>
).................................................................. 
<emphasis box="[1200,1221,944,965]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1234,1256,944,965]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1269,1346,944,965]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
u. 
<taxonomicName box="[1293,1346,944,965]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ossae">ossae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1359,1429,943,966]" captionStart="FIGURE 31" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1110,1134]" captionTargetBox="[533,1054,191,1078]" captionTargetId="figure-28@18.[522,1065,181,1086]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 31. Habitus of female of R. (R.) ungaricus ossae (Photo: Lech Karpiński)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655540/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
-. Punctuation of the pronotum uneven, the lateral areas are densely dotted, the central part is occupied by a smooth area that extends along its entire length and in which there are larger, deeper and sparse points; the central area of the disk is occupied by a smooth and flat surface (Figs 13,14,15,16,17); antennae in males reaching elytra apex, or surpassing it only by the last antennomere; prosternal process relatively broad and rounded at apex (
<figureCitation box="[905,963,1061,1083]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,829,853]" captionTargetId="figure-28@4.[463,1125,181,805]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Prosternal process." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6672420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6672420/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); lateral lobes of tegmen short and robust, almost parallel at ends, with external margin slightly convex; margin of phallobase roof almost straight, without hairs on top (
<figureCitation box="[1365,1424,1090,1112]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="7.[151,250,895,919]" captionTargetId="figure-19@7.[523,1064,181,871]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 9. Lateral lobes and phallobase roof." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6672430" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6672430/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Endemic to southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[468,526,1119,1141]" name="Spain" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">Spain</collectingCountry>
................................................... 
<emphasis box="[1135,1150,1120,1141]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1170,1185,1120,1141]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">R</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1204,1344,1119,1141]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
u. 
<taxonomicName authority="López &amp; Baena, 2022" authorityName="López &amp; Baena" authorityYear="2022" box="[1228,1344,1119,1140]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ropalopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occidentalis" status="ssp. nov.">occidentalis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1350,1436,1120,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1350,1436,1120,1141]" pageId="14" pageNumber="571" rank="subSpecies">ssp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</key>
